<p>There has always been the question of why God loves us. Ancient peoples believed that their gods loved them because of certain sacrifices they made or certain actions they may have performed in service to the gods. Christianity was brought into the picture later, and corrected this view somewhat, by saying that God loves us for nothing that we have done. This is, in fact, true; there is nothing that we have done or can do that can make God love us any differently. Over time, the Christian message has gotten twisted, and it is additionally said now that God loves us even though we are sinners, not deserving of such love. In this way, the message has been twisted from originally saying that God loves us regardless of our actions, to saying that God loves us <strong>despite</strong> our actions.</p>

<p>God loves us, of that we can be sure. God loves us, no matter what mistakes we might seem to make. There is a great fear that God will punish us, or be angry at us, for some misdeed that we have committed, and this is simply not true. Just as God loves us not for anything we have done, God will not stop loving us for anything we might do in the future.</p>

<p>As was pointed out in <a href="/jesus-message-17.html">Jesus' message for April 6, 2011</a>, this is because we have such a poor representation of love in our own world. When you are in a relationship with someone, you think that you must act in a certain way in order to make your partner happy. It happens all the time that people get divorced, because they simply can no longer get along. It occurs all too often that what once seemed like great love turns suddenly into immense hatred. There are simply very few examples here in this world of pure, unconditional love; the only example that may come close is the love of a parent, but even that can often be imperfect.</p>

<p>The reason is that most people love another person for their surface qualities and traits, usually either physical traits, personality, the way they act, or any combination of these. None of these things define who a person really is, for their soul is devoid of all of these. This is shown to be true because the mere fact that you love another, means that you do not love all people in the same way. You do not love all people in the same way, because they do not measure up to the standards that the person whom you love meets right now. Further, because you do not love all people in the same way, it is possible that the people whom you do love may fall out of your love because of something they do. Therefore, human love, by its very nature, is usually selfish and judgmental, based on desire, control, and fear. You will see later in a future article that love is not the only function of God that has become limited on the individual level. This is not to say, however, that human love cannot be exalted to a higher state, but this is only when one focuses on the light, not the darkness, and when one treats one's partner with true selflessness.</p>

<p>To gain more insight on how we should love others, let us shift to a higher perspective, and look to God looking upon His creation, and how God loves us. God is of pure love and light, and therefore so must His creation be of the same essence. God knows His own essence intimately, and loves it infinitely, because there is nothing within God that is not of love. In this act of love, He extends Himself into creation, and this creation possesses the very same essence as He. Therefore, God knows His creation intimately, and loves it infinitely, because there is nothing in it that is not of love. Because God loves us, His creation, infinitely, seeing His own essence in it, there is nothing that can be done to turn away that love.</p>

<p>This seems to leave a disparity, for we experience darkness in this world, yet here it is claimed that God only sees love and light, according to His own essence. God is not blind â€” of that we can be certain. Yet, why do we seem to experience darkness and separation? Despite our experience, the darkness is not real. God's creation, which in unison is called the Son, for it came from the Father, believed that it might be possible to be separate from God, and to act independently. This was what is now called the original sin, that God's Son thought He could act on His own. It must be known, however, that there was never any sin, for no separation is really possible. Yet, the Son persisted in believing in this separation, and in so doing, He denied His own nature of light, and so created the illusion of darkness within Himself.</p>

<p>This illusion of darkness, and denial of His own light nature, created an illusory world where there seemed to be both light and dark, good and evil, and where consciousness fragmented smaller and smaller, and thereby individuality was created. In essence, while the light is characterized by unity and expansion, the illusive dual world is characterized by separation and isolation. The fruit of the light is union, but the fruit of the darkness is separation. Because of this denial of our own nature, we feel guilt at the separation, for we believe we have separated from God. We have fear, because we believe that God will punish us for sinning against Him. How could it be true that God loves us if we have sinned in such a way? Because we have this immense inner darkness that we are afraid to face, we seek to project it upon others, or upon God Himself, so that we can be freed of it. This never works, however, because it only serves to focus on the darkness and strengthen the separation.</p>

<p>Therefore, what we see in others that we perceive to be bad, are often attributes that we really see within ourselves that we have not forgiven. The perceived darkness within ourselves is reflected onto others, and we attempt to separate ourselves from them so that we can be freed of this darkness and guilt.</p>

<p>You may try an exercise to demonstrate this to yourself. Choose anyone or anything that might annoy you. Look within yourself for a few moments, and contemplate what this annoyance shines a light on within yourself, that you have not forgiven. Forgive yourself, and see how you are transformed. You must be absolutely honest with yourself for this exercise to work.</p>

<p>We, then, perceive this darkness and even try to escape from it, but God does not see it, because it is not real. He only sees us in our true nature, as beings of love and light. He sees us as His own essence, which is infinitely good and of love. Further, he can see no darkness in us, because there is no darkness in Him. This is why God loves us infinitely, and cannot do otherwise, and there is nothing we can do to turn His love away, even if we should reject it for a time.</p>

<p>We must then draw a line to differentiate human, conditioned love from divine, unconditional love. Human love does little good, because there is always the fear of retribution or the loss of that love. When there is the fear of the lack of love, then there is no love to begin with. It is the nature of love to expand, not to ever contract, as human love can often do.</p>

<p>It should then be our goal to love as God loves us, so that we love all the same, with an infinite love that cannot be reduced in the least. This can only be done when we realize our own union with God, and the love that He has for us, for we cannot give something that we do not have. But when God's love flows through our souls, we cannot help but spread that love to all others equally, for all are of the same nature; all are one in Christ, and deserving of the love of God, and indeed such is their inheritance. In seeing us, then, God does not see what we have done or will do, but only sees who we are, seeing Himself in each one of us.</p>

<hr size="1" width="100%" align="Left" >

